  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "phenomenology-expert",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Mixed: Primary is fine, Ultimate and Secondary still problematic even as TNs",
    "content": "**Mixed.** One is fine, two are still problematic even as TNs.\n\n- **First Reality (TN: \"Primary Reality\")** -- Fine. \"Primary\" just means \"first in order of priority,\" which is exactly what 第一实在 is: the epistemically primary starting point. No ontological overreach. Helpful gloss.\n\n- **Zeroth Reality (TN: \"Ultimate Reality\")** -- Still problematic. The whole point of calling it \"Zeroth\" is that it is the reality traditional metaphysics *claims* is ultimate but which the author argues is inaccessible and becomes Second Reality when posited. A TN saying \"Ultimate Reality\" would give the reader the impression that the author endorses its ultimacy, when the author's position is precisely that there is no accessible ultimate reality. If a TN is wanted, something like \"the putative ground of phenomena\" or \"what traditional metaphysics calls ultimate reality\" would be more accurate -- it attributes the claim rather than endorsing it.\n\n- **Second Reality (TN: \"Secondary Reality\")** -- Still mildly problematic. \"Secondary\" connotes \"of lesser importance\" even in a footnote. But this is less damaging than \"Ultimate\" because footnotes are read with more interpretive charity. If the TN said \"Secondary Reality -- i.e., constructed upon First Reality\" the evaluative sting would be neutralized. Without that qualifier, I would prefer \"Derived Reality\" or \"Constructed Reality\" as the TN gloss -- both are descriptively accurate without implying inferiority.\n\n**Summary:** Keep the ordinal names in the main text (agreed). For TNs: \"Primary\" is good, replace \"Ultimate\" with something attributed (\"what traditional metaphysics calls ultimate reality\"), replace \"Secondary\" with \"Derived\" or \"Constructed.\""
  }
}
